text:
1. "The president made some very clear advice to pregnant American women and also children, which is, they should stop taking this drug." - this is highly irresponsible advice. As the controversial meta-study itself concludes: "While this association warrants caution, untreated maternal fever and pain pose risks such as neural tube defects and preterm birth, necessitating a balanced approach. We recommend judicious acetaminophen use‚Äîlowest effective dose, shortest duration‚Äîunder medical guidance, tailored to individual risk‚Äìbenefit assessments, rather than a broad limitation." In the UK (and I'm sure the US and other countries) this was already the standard advice.
2. "The prevalence of autism ... has exploded" - wrong and this is misleading people. The prevalence *of a label* has exploded. The label's diagnostic criteria have changed - broadened - over time. "In fairness" this video mentions that in the following sentence. But the video doesn't give it the weight it's due. And we can see from comments here that people are taking phrases like "the prevalence has exploded" literally. But the map is not the territory. The more non-disabled people who are added to a category that was mainly disabled people, the category will necessarily in frequency and decrease in severity. 
3. Leo Kanner published the first systematic identification of infantile autism in 1943. Autism wasn't included in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM) until 1980 (DSM III). Some commenters are saying when they were children they didn't know of any autistic children - well, if you were a child before 1980 those children would have been labeled retards or schizophrenics or such. Read The Diagnosis of Autism: From Kanner to DSM-III to DSM-5 and Beyond for a description of how the diagnoses and labels changed.
4. "A diagnosis of ASD now includes several conditions that used to be diagnosed separately: autistic disorder, pervasive developmental disorder not otherwise specified (PDD-NOS), and Asperger syndrome. Your doctor or other healthcare provider can help you understand and navigate the diagnostic process." - CDC
5. Read the Scientific American article, Does Tylenol Use during Pregnancy Cause Autism? What the Research Shows.
6. Please stop sane-washing what Trump says.

text: As a nurse and an EMT, my first recommendation is to discuss your daily pain with your doctor. You need to be honest about how often you use any pain meds, over the counter or prescription. NSAIDS like ibuprofen are metabolized through the kidneys. Paracetamol/Acetaminophen/Tylenol is metabolized by the liver. If you have an issue with EITHER OR BOTH of these organs due to diabetes or heavy drinking, or any other reason, you need to be VERY careful of the amount and kind of any medications you take.

text:
Paracetamol/acetaminophen reduces pain by blocking the brains chemical messengers letting you know you are in pain (also affecting the messageners that control body temperature).

Ibuprofen reduces pain by reducing the inflammation/swelling causing pain.

Paracetamol/acetaminophen is typically better for headaches or pain unrelated to inflammation, ibuprofen is better for wound pain or other inflammation related pain. In many cases, they are best used together, but always check if there's a reason you shouldn't use one and neither are good for long term regular use.

I feel like this video doesn't actually explain the differences and uses of the medications very well üòÖ

text:
Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD), while only recently defined by modern medicine, has likely existed throughout human history. Historical perceptions varied greatly across cultures; some individuals exhibiting autistic traits were mistakenly regarded as possessed, gifted, or simply as having a disability. The significant increase in diagnosed cases since the 1980s is a primary focus of contemporary research. A key question is whether this rise reflects improved diagnostic criteria and awareness, or if it might also involve environmental factors such as chemical exposures, dietary changes, or other modern influences.

#donaldtrump #autism #health #breakingnews 

Donald Trump and his Health and Human Services Secretary, Robert F. Kennedy Jr, are now speaking at the White House. They‚Äôre making the announcement we were expecting, tying pregnant women‚Äôs use of the painkiller paracetamol to autism in children.

Acidosis , pH < 7.3

text:
1. Arterial pH-based Criteria:
1. Arterial pH < 7.3 (metabolic acidosis) despite adequate fluid resuscitation, OR Serum lactate > 3.5 mmol/L after fluid resuscitation, OR Serum lactate > 3 mmol/L after early resuscitation (before fluid replacement)
2. Clinical and Biochemical-based Criteria: Prothrombin time (PT) > 100 seconds (INR > 6.5), AND
Serum creatinine > 3.4 mg/dL (> 300 Œºmol/L), AND
Grade III/IV hepatic encephalopathy
